history.content:
Lectures are focused on good design principles, like task analysis, using personas and the iterative design process. You do not learn any actual tools or services in lecture and they are covered at an extremely high level in section--there is a large amount of self learning and hacking things together to make stuff work "enough" to be a good prototype in this class. The second half of the class drops the lecture format to work with your group in a studio format, where you basically just meet up to get stuff done on your own and maybe ask a TA/GSI for tips/design critiques.
For this reason, you will not learn front end development in this class any more than you would for developing your own projects. The case for 160 is just that it's a project with other people that have different skillsets, and there is usually an application type that is focused on (last semester was smart watches, this semester is alexa/voice). Take the class if you would enjoy working in a diverse group like that, and need some basics in design principles.
You will still have to self teach android, html/css, etc even if you take this class. If your sole purpose is to learn something like web or android development, I would recommend you just follow along a YouTube tutorial, because that is essentially what you will have to do anyway if you take the class.

TLDR; Lectures cover basic design principles, discussion covers tools at a very high level. You will be self learning front end anyway if you take this class.

I'm not really interested in doing UI/UX as a career but I don't really know any front-end at all and this seems like the only class that teaches this (which I find strange if the department claims to create Full-Stack Engineers)? Would I be able to take this along with 2 other average difficulty techs?
